{"/service/ndnp/dlc/batch_dlc_2hayden_ver02/data/sn83045462/0028060494A/1949040501/0333.xml":{"full_text":"American Security\nAnd Peoples Drug\nShares Active\nBy Edward C. Stone\nPeoples Drug and American Se-\u00bb\neurity <Sz Trust Co. stocks figured!\nmuch more prominently in March\ntrading on the Washington Stock\nExchange than in any- other re\ncent month, the official summary,]\nout today, discloses. Trading in]\nPeoples Drug totaled 595 shares\nand in American Security, 360\nshares.\nMarch trading in all issues\nreached 25 272 shares against 25,\n484 in February and 14,304 in\nMarch a year ago. Potomac Elec\ntric Power common again headed\nthe list with a turnover of 13.230\nshares, far above the February\ntotal.\nVirginia Electric Power com\nmon. with sales of 2,756 shares.]\nand Washington Gas common\nwith a turnover of 2,824. were fol-\nlowed by American Telephone,]\nsales reaching 1,711 shares. Gar-]\nfinckel and Hecht shares and j\nLahston Monotype w>ere among]\nthe more active issues in a month j\nthat saw some of the liveliest\ntrading sessions on record.\nHirsch Expands Office.\nHirsch Co., members of the\nNew York Stock Exchange, today\nannounced the establishment in'\nthe Washington branch at 1624 Ij\nstreet N.W. of a mutual fund de-]\npartment under the management\nof F. R. Chatfield.\nMr. Chatfield was the originator\nand president of the F. R. Chat\nfield Co. of Boston, and has had\n20 years\u2019 experience in the study\nand sale of mutual fund shares.!\nHe was born and educated in Eng\nland, w'here these funds got their\nstart. The manager of the Wash\nington office is Oscar Coolican.\nFurniture Dealers Confer.\nLeaders in the National Retail\nFurniture Association held a re\ngional conference at the Shoreham\nHotel today. 'Tomorrow's Busi\nness\u201d was the general theme.\nShort luncheon talks were made\nby Don Jordan, Roanoke; Walter\nSchob, Philadelphia; James G.\nLaw. Bloomsburg, Pa., and John\nW. Craig, Cincinnati, all manu\nfacturers, who discussed ''The\nHome Goods Outlook.\u201d\nLawrence Clayton, member. Fed\neral Reserve Board, was to address\nthe afternoon session on Regula\ntion W\u201d; W. J. Lockwood, Housing\nAuthority, on \u2018Housing Prospects\nand the Home Goods Industry,\u201d\nand Dexter M. Keezer of Business\nWeek, on the \"Business Outlook.\u201d\nMaury Nee will preside at a din\nner this evening, with Senator\nO Mahoney as guest speaker.\nFinancial District Note*.\nThe McElfresh Agency of the\nConnecticut Mutual Life Insurance\nCo. today was host to Frederick\nO. Lyter of Hartford, superin\ntendent of agencies. The agency\nis now 100 years old, having been\nestablished in March, 1849. when\nZachary Taylor was President.\nTrading is expected to pick up\nshortly in Pepco preferreds on the\nWashington Stock Exchange as\nthese issues are not to be called.\nI Business Briefs\nBusiness Failures increased to\n216 in the week ended March 31,\nlargest total since May 21. 1942,\nand compared with 166 in the 1\nprevious week, 91 in the like 1948\nweek and 310 in the like 1939\nweek\u2014Dun Bradstreet.\nMember Firm Borrowings ex\npanded to $396,341,730 on March i\n31 vs. $313,208,979 a month earlier!\nand $272,317,195 a year earlier\u2014:\nNew York Stock Exchange.\nBush Terminal Building Co.\nstockholders rejected a manage\nment proposal to split common\nshares 20 for 1.\nAppalachian Power Co. asked\nSEC permission to borrow $18.\n000,000 from four banks.\nGeneral Public Utilities Corp.\nasked SEC permission to offer 787.\n644 shares of its common stock\nholdings in New York State Elec\ntric <fc Gas Corp. to General hold\ners at $41 a share.\nNational City Bank of New York\nreported net income for the first\n1949 quarter was $4,761,005 or 77\ncents a share vs. $4,567,822 or 73\ncents a year earlier.\nKroger Co. sales in four weeks\nended March 26 totaled $64,600,\n071 or 3% above a year ago.\nSouthern Pacific Transportation\nSystem had a deficit of $1,304,387\nin two months ended February 28\nvs. net income of $4,325,772 or $1.15\na share in the same 1948 period.\nTide Water Associated Oil Co.\nearned $38,618,000 or $6.04 a share\nin 1948 vs. $29,230,000 or $4.57 in\nthe previous year.\nWest Penn Electric Co. and sub-1\nsldiaries had net income of $10,\n906.897 or $3.68 in 1948 vs. $9,\n482.889 or $3.07 in 1947.\nGeneral Aniline Film Corp.\nearned 88.604.919 in 1948 vs. $3,\n333,250 in the previous year.\nInternational Cellucotton Prod\nucts Co. profit for 1948 was $7,\n100,686 or $5.97 vs. $3,787,535 or\n$8.19 in 1947.\nAnaconda Wire A Cable Co.\nearned $7,009,136 or $8.30 in 19481\nvs. $8,480,513 or $10.05 in the|\nprevious year.\nDravo Corp. net income for 1948\nwas $4,195,825 or $8.28 vs. $3.\n639.831 or $7.20 in 1947.\nStone A Webster. Inc., earned\n$6,494 598 or $3.09 in 1948 vs. $2.\n568.702 or $1.22.\nColonial Mills, Inc., profit for\nthree months ended February 28\nwas $898,352 or $1.08 vs. $2,292,229\nor $2.88 a year earlier.\nPeter Paul. Inc., earned $3,388.\n670 or $4.97 in 1948 vs. $2,682,155\nor $3.94 in the previous year.\nClimax Molybdenum Co. net for\n1948 was $2,618,460 or $1.04 vs.\n$2,432,210 or 97 cents in 1947.\nEastern Air Lines, Inc., earned\n$2,346,871 or 98 cents in 1948 vs.\n$1,259,196 or 53 cents.\nWarner Co. net for 1948 was $2.\n275,897 or $4.79 vs. $1,580,535 or\n$3.33 in 1947.\nA. Stein A Co. earned $2,046,377\nor $4.33 in 1948 vs. $1,967,023 or\n$4.17 in the previous year.\nUnited States Printinr A Llth\nefraphinc Co. profit for 1948 was\n$1,956,433 or $11.12 vs. $2,720,768\nfar $15.84 in 1947.\nUnited Stores Corp. earned $1,\n742,397 in 1948 vs. $1,683,229 in\nthe previous year.\nBuffalo Bolt Co. net for 1948\nOr as $1,862,319 or $4.59 vs. $1,666,\n940 or $4.16 in 1947.\nN. Y. STOCK EXCHANGE\niFamljked b* the Aasorlated PreM l\nBales\u2014\nStock -uo Add Set\nDividend Rats 00 thrb Law. 1 rh*e\nABBOTT L- \u00abOa 1 773* 77g* 7 73* 4 14\nA C P-Brlll Mot 2 2*4 24a 24a *4\nAdams Ex 110* 17 1#3, 183* 18\u00bb\u00ab *4\nAddr